                    <td width="100%" colspan="2" valign="top" align="left">
                      <div align="center">
                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%" bgcolor="#004242">
                              <p align="center" style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 150%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><b><font size="2" face="Tahoma" color="#FFFFFF">DESCRIPTION</font></b></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr><td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">
For most people, the newbie levels are terrible.  Constant fear of death, horrendous downtime and lack of dynamic as a character.  Not only is it a right of passage for level 20, (the surname and stats affect character more) but it's really where the game begins.  Wit that in mind, you want to attain the 20th level as soon as possible.  There is, hands down, no better place on Norrath to do this than the Field of Bone.
<br><br>
First things first: can you go to Field of Bone?  By this I mean, are you KOS and will you be able to take advantage of the guards?  If you're an Iksar, the answer is a resounding 'yes.'  But if you of any other race, some things must be taken into consideration.  For starters, are you on a PvP server?  If you are, and you're a light race, DON'T come here.  But if your preference is Dark Elf, Ogre, or Troll, then come on over.  All races should feel welcome if you are on a non-PvP server.  
<br><br>
Next up?  Bind points.  After some faction changing, (it will come in time, con the wandering guards from a distance) feel free to bind in Cabilis.  For you Iksar, your bind point is actually IN the field of bone, and this is a great thing.  If you don't have the luxury of an FoB bind, the Overthere and Firiona Vie provide binding points with a considerable travel time.  The Overthere zones directly into Warsliks Wood, which zones directly into Field of Bone.  The Firiona Vie path takes you to the Swamp of No Hope, to the Field of Bone.  Spend fifteen minutes looking at the maps and get familiar with what these zones look like, it is more than worth your time.
<br><br>
Now that you're bound and you're in the Field of Bone, let me point out some of the landmarks here.  First off, there's Cabilis, highly visible in the southwest corner of the map, there are merchants here that will buy items, as well as distribute some quests.  There is a quest with bone chips in the ruins, but my advice would be to save those chips.  Bone chips are the staple item of choice since Necros will pay well for them in stacks (of 20.)  As well as the East Cabilis Zone, there are also zones to the Swamp (to the south), Warsliks Woods (west by northwest), and the Emerald Jungle(southeast.)  The Emerald Jungle zone should be avoided altogether.  It's far beyond your level and the Targishin (more on him in a moment) spawns in the ruins near the zone.  The other two are good for running to if you need to zone and Cabilis is not an option.  Next landmark is where you'll be putting in your dues: the actually pit of bone.  More will be presented on this area when we get to the leveling portion of this document.  Kurn's Tower is on the northeast edge of the pit.  The area around the tower is still dangerous, the scaled wolves will shred a sub-lvl 10 character fairly quickly, and they agro.  Next up are the two underground compounds towards the west side of the map.  One is empty, one has spiderlings, as you know, the spiders group, so stay out of here at a young level (it might be a good idea to take on a group or two of them at lvl 4 or so, where they're easy kills that do little damage, but yield a small amount of exp in especially in volume.)  And finally we have the beach.  There's a wandering ghost, leave her alone for the time being, she won't attack.  There also two large islands out in the ocean, STAY AWAY, there's a level 50+ ape that's quick, and VERY deadly.  It's impossible for him to aggro unless you go out there testing your luck.  To the eastern end of the beach, you'll notice some columns sticking up out of the water, blow them is an underground Sythrax compound.  Gharg Oberlord is down there and is part of a large quest much, much later in the game.  However, if you're an Iksar everything down there is non-agro, and you might want to check it out for aesthetic reasons.  And the final landmark in Field of bone?  On the western end of the beach there's a cave, commonly referred to as the marauder cave.  You'll be taking advantage of it towards the end of your Field of Bone session, and it will be discussed in detail at a later time.
<br><br>
Now, what you've been waiting for:  what to fight, where to fight, when to fight.  First start on the path by the Cabilis zone.  If you're non-Iksar keep in mind that there is a lone wandering guard that travels down from the gates so fight off of the path (considerably off the path, keep the Warsliks zone in mind for a zone line here.)  Start out here with scaled wolf pups, keep in mind they group so try and snag the stragglers.  With 8 or so of these guys, you'll be level two.  If you're not financially equipped (twinked) then save items off of corpses (looting keeps lag down as not so many dead corpses will be lying around.) At this point, you might want to risk taking on scorpions one at a time.  But once you're level three, take on scale wolf pups en masse (3 or more at a time.)  A trick I use instead of pulling, is get two or three on you, kill 2 and run around with him on you into other scale wolf pups, they'll aggro.  With this technique you can keep a constant flow of mobs on you, and gain the exp bonus since you're taking on more than one at once.  Once you're level four or even five, you'll need to use the same technique on scorps, but they will require a tap (taunting works also.) At this point you can alternate with fencers as well, those and the carrion class will agro in groups all the same.
<br><br>
Once you should work effectively here for quite some time.  At thiattain level 6 (we're talking 2 hours tops, with discretion [when to run] this is a great exp spot,) it's time for the pit.  Down the path you've been fighting next to for so long, is the main entrance to the pit.  Take my advice, and do not pull to this area.  Overcrowding often happens which means trains.  There's a perfectly good pit entrance down the interior wall in either direction.  Pull solo at this point.  Skeletons work well, as do bonebinders.  Bone binders drop webs, which can be combined with a tailoring kit in twos to create swatches.  Swatches are used to make raw and cured silk armor (the latter being the better of the two.)  Soloing s point it might be advisable to group with a second individual simply to reduce downtime.  Continue pulling the suggested mobs, until you find greater skeletons yellow (with two people, otherwise stick with evens.  Using this method and moving progressively north in the field (mobs increase in level the further north you move) you can quickly get to level 12.  One thing to remember however, is STAY OUT OF THE PIT, only stick to the interior walls.  Never make the mistake of getting the pit other than to pull.  Try and stick with the heretic Iksar (bandits, brigands and footpads) when possible to raise faction with the Legion of Cabilis (this will allow you non-natives to bind near this zone.)  Using these tactics and reminders, you can move effectively, and efficiently.
<br><br>
Once you're 12+ it's time to move over to the base of Kurn's Tower.  It's the fairly interesting looking structure to the northeast end of the pit.  Along the backside of the tower is the ramp to the entrance, this is your new home.  The good part here is, that after binding near the entrance to the tower zone (FoB side, not IN the tower) even death is only a matter of running down the side of the tower, and recovering your corpse so long as you bind.  Non-native melee classes still have a run, (unless you took my advice with the iksar heretics above) but with two people here you should be safe.  The great part is you're still next to a zone line even though you're not fighting near the guards.  With all of this in mind, start pulling.  Keep to burynai excavators and greater scalebones and slowly work to fencer classes as well as heartsting scorpions.  Only pull one at a time, always pull and make sure both characters are pulling their own weight.  You can move to level 17 fairly quickly employing this tactic, you might even want to hold out until 18 because once this short lived spawn is up, it's time for the most dangerous part of the Field of Bone: The Iksar Cave.
<br><br>
The Iksar cave is tricky, partly because the mobs are almost impossible to pull one at a time, and also because a higher level mob (Kerosh Blackhand) randomly spawns and can bring down a beating on the party fairly quickly.  If he's up, get a higher level mob to alleviate the problem if your group can't take care of him.  Here's the gameplan for the cave: one man pull and the group hangs out on the beach outside.  The more the merrier is essentially the group philosophy here.  Definitely get someone with sow, you WILL have to run at some point during this spawn.  Now to the actual fighting.  Inside there's usually a wandering marauder in the hallway to the hideout, he can be pulled outside solo.  Next, once the hall is clear, the puller needs to take a quantitative look inside the hideout.  There's generally two to three mobs on either side of the hideout (I can't express how important it is to move slowly and make sure of all the mob's locations.)  As I stated earlier, it's impossible to pull one without a lull or mez.  Pulling one on the right side, will pull all on the right side, same goes for pulling from the left (pulling fom the left tends to also pull everyone from the right as well.)  So take the right group first, cast a spell down the hall a bit on one of the mobs and run outside assuming you have three on your tail.  Using the assist function, and all of the members taking an active role, 3 mobs shouldn't be an issue.  With a full group, and a combination of crowd control (fear, mez, etc.) taking on 6 might not be terribly hard, although post-fight downtime should be expected.  Once the first room is clear however, there's a tiny room in the far back where the uncommon Kerosh spawns.  With this in mind, you can usually see the storm coming, (Kerosh) and group deaths can be avoided altogether with the quick planning of a higher level player in zone dispatching Kerosh.  Using these tactics, you should be able to bust through to level 20 without much trouble.  You can reach 22-23 as well by decreasing group players from 6 to as far down as 2.  Once you're done here, make your move to the Lake of Ill Omen.
<br><br>
Extras: If you're doing the Iksar caves, and a you're ready for a fight but the rest of the group is still medding/resting, make sure to do some swimming, just stay away from the island.  If the group disbands, and you want to continue with a new group.  Swim to the northwest corner of the ocean (watch for the ape island) and into the zone corner and face up.  Coordinate your new group while your swimming goes up.  Before you laugh or ask, 200 swimming is amazing.  You WILL have to swim eventually since you'll eventually end up taking the boat in the Overthere someday.  Cabilis navigation increases twofold with 200 swimming.  And rest assured, between the Temple of Cazic-Thule, Guk, and other water-filled zones, you WILL appreciate the 200 swim.
<br><br>
With the new experience system, don't fear grouping with 5 other individuals.  
<br><br>
Languages can always be improved.
<br><br>
Low level magic spells (true north, poison cloud, amog others) should be cast frequently.  Two reasons, they're relatively cheap in mana the higher your level, and they increase spell skill numbers just as well as their more expensive upgrade spells.
<br><br>
And on a final note, there are other ways to do this zone.  This is the streamlined version for those of you that want to combine efficiency with speed.  At level 20 your strength starts to affect your damage (there's a damage cap that is lifted) all other stat start having effects on your character, I just wanted to get you there as soon as possible.
                           </font></td>
                          </tr>
